Mamming: Coronavirus mass infections: 174 farmhands infected
Following a coronavirus mass infection in a large vegetable farm in Mamming in lower Bavaria, nearly 500 people are under quarantine and not allowed to leave the farm.
A security service is monitoring the confinement.
A total of 174 farmhands tested positive for the coronavirus pathogen Sars-CoV-2 during mass testing, as the district office of Dingolfing-Landau announced on Saturday evening.
“To prevent further spread, we unfortunately need to take this step to protect the population,” stated district administrator Werner Bumeder (CSU).
Seven employees were previously infected on the farm - this was the reason for the mass testing.
The business is a large vegetable farm, which cultivates raspberries, cucumbers, cabbages and beets - but the cucumbers are only for pickling jars.
Mamming is a rural community with approximately 3,300 residents, not far from Dingolfing’s large BMW plant.
Bumeder appealed to the citizens to stay calm: “According to our information, this is a closed group of people.”
On the farm, infected employees were kept separated from non-infected employees, and the premises are now surrounded by a fence.
The Green and SPD parties blamed the state government.
The two opposing factions accused Minister-President Markus Söder (CSU) and his cabinet of failing to control the seasonal workers’ accommodation.
“This could pay dearly if local infections like this spread and regional lockdowns have to be arranged,” said Jürgen Mistol, the parliamentary director of the Green Party.
The SPD sees it very similarly: “After the coronavirus outbreak in the Wiesenhof butchery in mid-May, we called for a special control program, including for farms with seasonal workers,” said environmental expert Florian von Brunn.
“The hygiene conditions in the workplace and the living conditions need to be heavily controlled, in our opinion.
Obviously this didn’t happen.”
The outbreak happened “on cue.”
