Discussion about scrapping the 50+1 rule
Former DFB President Reinhard Grindel has recommended thought be given to scrapping the 50+1 rule.
“German football should at least discuss setting conditions and clear rules for investors before the EU Commission creates any fait accompli,” Grindel told “Bild am Sonntag”.
He said, “In any case the 50+1 rules don’t work for those clubs that are most likely to threaten Bayern and Dortmund - look at Leipzig or Leverkusen.
In any case, you can’t get around the debate as to whether it shouldn’t be made easier for clubs that are aiming to break into this grouping to engage investors.
But he doubts whether there is a willingness within the German football league to allow majority shareholdings which are prohibited by the 50+1 rule in the Bundesliga.
“There is a legal risk involved in putting up investment barriers around the Bundesliga as a business hub in a European internal market,” said Grindel.
The former DFB boss sees a danger that “the attempts to create a greater competitive balance in the Bundesliga could, in the end, merely weaken the competitiveness of our top clubs at European level, but not lead to more suspense in the championship”.
Even evenly distributing TV monies will not have any decisive effect.
“FC Bayern have revenues of 750 million euros, Borussia Dortmund 500 million and RB Leipzig 300 million.
So even between the top three clubs there are immense differences.
The other 15 clubs have an average budget of 130 million,” explained the 58 year old.
Looking back, Grindel feels betrayed.
“Unfortunately, there were individuals who noticed that error and went to the press rather than speak to me about it,” said Grindel about his acceptance of an expensive watch, which led to his resignation in April 2019.
“On a human level, that hurt me a lot”.
He had received the gift, valued at around 11,000 euros, from a Ukrainian functionary.
“I committed a compliance violation and it was right to accept the consequences,” said Grindel.
“I was completely transparent and honest about the dubious gift of the watch.
Many people at the DFB knew about it”.
He had never “made any secret of the gift”, affirmed the 58 year old.
“You might call that naive, but this type of transparency was the complete opposite of corruption”.
