Bavaria: At least four dead on Bavaria’s roads at the weekend
The fine weather drew bikers onto the roads in many places.
For at least three people, their bike ride ended in death.
An 18 year old pedestrian was also killed.
Schönthal - Several people, mostly young, died on Bavaria’s roads at the weekend.
Near Schönthal (Cham rural district) on Sunday, an 18 year old woman riding a motorbike was hit by an oncoming car that crossed into her lane.
Why the vehicle strayed into her lane was initially unclear.
In Upper Bavaria on Saturday, a 22 year old on a bike collided with a horse-drawn carriage.
According to police, he was riding downhill near Beilngries.
He collided with the carriage on a left-hand bend.
His injuries were so severe that he died at the scene.
Of the twelve occupants in the carriage, one man was seriously injured and one man sustained mild injuries, said the police.
An 18 year old died in another fatal accident in Bad Kötzting, in Upper Palatinate.
Late on Saturday night, he had lain down on a road and he was run over by a 42 year old driver.
The police believe that the 18 year old was trying to sleep.
The driver was unable to brake in time.
On Saturday near Schönberg (Freyung-Grafenau rural district), a 57-year-old biker hit a car head-on on a right-hand bend despite braking hard.
He died at the scene.
The 57 year old female driver suffered shock, while the other three people in the car were unhurt.
Bavaria’s Transport Minister Kerstin Schreyer (CSU) touched on the subject of motorcyclist safety on Saturday.
In a letter to Gabor Kovacs, the organizer of the biker protests against driving bans which are planned for August, the Minister referred to substantial investments such as underride guards on crash barriers, and the straightening of dangerous bends.
“We have done a lot for motorcyclist safety in recent years,” said the letter.
“The number of motorcyclist fatalities has fallen by around 28 percent compared with 2011”.
