“Gone With The Wind”: Film legend Olivia de Havilland dies
Film legend and Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland has died.
She died of natural causes on Sunday in Paris at the age of 104, her spokeswoman told the Deutsche Presse agency.
de Havilland was known for her role as Melanie Hamilton in the southern states epic “Gone With The Wind” (1939).
Born in Tokyo to British parents, de Havilland moved to California as a young child.
Austrian dramatist Max Reinhardt discovered the 19 year old playing the role of Hermia in Shakespeare’s “Midsummer Night’s Dream”.
The Warner Brothers film studio immediately took her under contract for seven years and made her famous alongside Errol Flynn.
She made eight films with the heart-throb.
In 1946 she won her first Oscar with the leading role in "To Each His Own".
In Germany the film ran under the title “Mutterherz”.
Three years later came the Best Actress award for her role in William Wyler’s "The Heiress".
She also won great acclaim as a neurotic eccentric in “The Dark Mirror” and “The Snake Pit”.
In 1952 Daphne du Maurier suggested her for the leading role in the adaptation of her novel “My Cousin Rachel”.
The film was a worldwide success.
In “Hush...Hush, Sweet Charlotte” she acted alongside her old friend Bette Davis.
Her marriage to novelist Marcus Goodrich (1946 to 1953) produced son Benjamin.
In Paris, de Havilland married journalist Pierre Paul Galante, with whom she had daughter Gisèle.
The marriage also ended.
Rumors of an affair with former British prime minister Edward Heath were never confirmed.
