Kalbitz sacking from Alternative from Germany confirmed - FDP speaks of “fig leaf”
The expulsion of Andreas Kalbitz from the AfD is only a “fig leaf” from the FDP’s point of view and doesn’t change anything about the party’s character.
“The AfD is the parliamentary arm of the far-right in Germany.
Andreas Kalbitz is just the tip of the iceberg of the radicals in the AfD,” FDP interior politician Benjamin Strasser told the news agency dpa in Berlin.
The Federal Arbitration Court of the AfD confirmed the expulsion of Kalbitz on Saturday in Stuttgart after several hours of deliberation, the Federal Executive Committee had decided this in May by majority.
Kalbitz is the chair of the AfD faction in the Brandenburg state parliament.
“If the AfD were really serious about consistently removing right wing extremists from their party, officials such as Björn Höcke and his followers would have been removed long ago,” says Strasser.
“However, there is no political will in the AfD, because right-wing extremism is now part of the party.”
CSU secretary general Markus Blume expressed a similar opinion: “The fact that Andreas Kalbitz is excluded now says nothing and changes nothing,” he told the “Welt am Sonntag.”
"Instead, it says a lot about how many frenetic supporters a right-wing extremist still has in the AfD.”
Blume assumes that the AfD will continue to land less than 5 percent in future elections.
“The AfD’s days in the parliaments are numbered.”
Kalbitz was one of the advocates of the official, now disbanded, “wing” around the Thuringia AfD state and faction chair Björn Höcke, which had been classified as a “secured right-wing extremist endeavor” by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution.
In May, the AfD federal board threw Kalbitz out of the party.
The reason they gave was that Kalbitz was a former member or the now forbidden right-wing extremist group “Heimattreue Deutsche Jugend” (HDJ) when he joined the party and did not tell the Republicans.
Kalbitz denies the membership in the HDJ.
The chair of the left-wing faction in the Brandenburg state parliament, Sebastian Walter, emphasizes that the decision of the federal arbitration court doesn’t change anything about the character of the AfD: “This is still a wolf in sheep’s clothing.
The AfD is still a right-wing extremist party, with or without Kalbitz.”
Neither the federal party nor the right wing will be weakened by this decision.
“The Meuthan squad’s maneuver is transparent.
They want to evade further observation by the Federal Office for the Protection of the Constitution and are trying to fly under the radar,” says Walter.
“The AfD won’t be rid of the spirits they have conjured up.
A removal changes nothing,” says the Brandenburg SPD secretary general Erik Stohn about the decision in the Kalbitz case.
“The AfD state association and the faction stood by their right-wing leader until today.”
The legal dispute about Kalbitz’s membership in the AfD will continue.
On Saturday, Kalbitz announced he will dispute the decision of the federal arbitration court in civil court.
