Juventus of Turin Italian champions
Turin - After a redeeming goal from Cristiano Ronaldo, Juventus of Turin, who hold the record for the number of Italian league championships won, have secured the title for the ninth time in a row.
The team, including five players dubbed World Footballer Of The Year wrapped up their 36th Scudetto in the club’s history on Sunday evening by winning 2:0 (1:0) in their home game against Sampdoria of Genoa.
Ronaldo scored to make it 1:0 before half-time.
With two more matchdays to go before the Serie A season ends, Turin have 83 points and can no longer be knocked off top spot, but are playing without former German international Sami Khedira who has been injured for some time.
Inter Milan, who are currently second in the table, are seven points behind.
In the first half, despite their apparent superiority, Juventus caused little threat, but then Ronaldo scored from a set-piece free kick in the last action before the break.
With a low shot, the 35 year old converted a Miralem Pjanic pass from the edge of the area (45+7).
With the visitors now attacking more, Ronaldo was also involved in making it 2:0, after Federico Bernardeschi (67) helped with his shot.
That ensured the lacklustre but crucial victory.
When he hit the bar from a penalty in the 89th minute, only Ronaldo himself, with one eye on the battle to be top scorer, would have really been annoyed.
“It’s tough to stay on the ball, both mentally and physically, for 90 minutes.
The games are strange and the momentum changes very easily,” explained coach Maurizio Sarri after the 1:2 against Udinese on Thursday.
In particular, his players were mentally exhausted, said the Juve coach.
The defeat meant that the Turin outfit was unable to seal the title in a perfect manner.
Recently Juve have had their rivals’ weaknesses to thank for the gap at the top of the table, which was comfortable in the end.
Because Sarri’s team had only won five out of the eleven matches prior to Sunday’s game.
And whether Ronaldo will end up top scorer is questionable.
For while the Portuguese superstar has scored 31 goals so far, after his hat trick in the 5:1 (1:1) against fourth-placed Lazio of Rome, former Dortmund star Ciro Immobile has 34 goals to his name - as many as Robert Lewandowski contributed in FC Bayern’s title win.
Gonzalo Higuaín, now with Juve, holds the Italian record.
The Argentinian scored 36 goals for SSC Napoli in the 2015/2016 season.
The next opportunity for the “Old Lady” of Italian football to win a trophy will come in August.
Juventus are in the quarter final of the Champions League, but they have to make good a 0:1 deficit from the first leg against Olympique Lyonnais on 7th August if they are to reach the final tournament in Lisbon.
Real Madrid or Manchester City would await them as their opponent in the next knockout round.
